Imagine you are building a system to manage a Zoo. You have a stable hierarchy of classes representing different animals: Lion, Penguin, and Dolphin.

Over time, your boss asks you to add new behaviors to these animals:

First, they need a feed() method.

Next week, they need a checkHealth() method.

Next month, they need an exportToJson() method for a new database.

If you keep adding these methods to the Animal classes, the classes become bloated, violating the Single Responsibility Principle. 
Furthermore, every time you add a new behavior, you risk breaking existing code because you have to modify every single animal class.

The Solution: The Visitor Pattern
The Visitor pattern suggests moving these operational behaviors out of the Animal classes and into a separate class called a Visitor.

Instead of the Lion knowing how to export itself to JSON, or how a Vet checks its health, the Lion just needs to know one simple thing: How to accept a visitor.

The "Secret Sauce": Double Dispatch
The magic of the Visitor pattern relies on a concept called Double Dispatch. It means the method that gets executed depends on two things:

The type of the Visitor (e.g., is it a Vet or a DataExporter?)

The type of the Element being visited (e.g., is it a Lion or a Penguin?)
